post_body_text: Part 1  Interview with local non profit out of Charlotte, NC who has been on the ground since second day after biblical flooding devastated Western North Carolina.  This interview was conducted after a long day of running around the mountainside. We were shocked to find out that the area has been swarmed with donations from the region and from across the country. Everyday people really stepped up to help others when in need.  As a member of Congress I vow to introduce legislation to bailout all homeowners whose homes were lost during the flood.  We need to be sending billions to Western North Carolina/East Tennessee rather than to Ukraine and Israel!! We discuss how towns are changed forever, the important work her group does with Veterans in this region, the worry and hardship that school districts have with locating unnaccounted for students, and overall lacking federal response.  Harbaugh4congress.com #ashevillenc #hurricanehelene #disasterrelief #hurricane #northcarolina #flood #congress #trump #maga #harriswaltz2024üíôüíôüíô #voteblue #biden #independent #greenparty #daytonohio #dayton #937ohio
GoogleAudioText: Michael was the worst hurricane we've seen. The SESC, the River Flods and Pennsylvania was the worst flooding we'd ever seen. This is like a combination of both of those temples. And it's been really difficult. Because this is also so close to my home. Our organizations takes veterans into these mountains for hikes, for mental wellness and wellbeing. We teach kids about the environment. And now I feel like I have to switch gears and start teaching kids about natural disasters. How to be prepared, how to keep themselves safe. I think the delay in federal response created a vacuum that the community just immediately filled with some sort of things. And support and supplies and everything that people need, even rescue and recovery efforts. Discussed with people and like tell people how these communities and houses are cut off and how literally the river, how the river is in new places. The river is in new places. So where the road used to run along the river, the river took out the road entirely and is now there where the road was. So it's not just a matter of establishing asphalt. It's a matter of having to build a bridge over a new river for miles. If you wanted the road to go back in the same place, the other issue that we're having is the riverbed is now anywhere between 25 and 40 feet deeper than it was. So instead of being like a nice plain that like farm valley with a creek running through it, it is a, it looks like a valley with a huge cavern, 40 foot deep cavern running through it. So where these roads were, there's no more ground underneath that to just lay asphalt on. It's catastrophic. People are forced with either walking up the side of a mountain and then down and out. And so extremely rigorous. Her and her team is considering and plan in the planning stages of, you know, they're going to have to start backpacking in, you know, maybe actually blade trailblazing. And you know, we're getting helicopters, you know, dropping it. And to get you guys like some idea of the catastrophe, it's very hard to see because you, as you saw coming in, the difference between Swan and O. Black Mountain old four. And then driving up through Morganton and kind of around that eastern side and just Bruce Pine, it didn't, you didn't see a lot of damage. What you don't see are all the little haulers that got destroyed and all the little communities that got destroyed right along the river, right along the creek. Landslides took out entire like, you know, gatherings of homes. The lady here was actually just telling me that they still have 163 kids in the school system that are unaccounted for. And this area looks like it's really well supported, really well off. We're hearing this. They have gasoline. They have a national guard. But we still have a lot of people missing. And this is what I'm talking about, you know, the disaster relief. You know, we're sending money to the rich and the powerful and overseas when where is the well put in place plan to deal with disasters. Hurricane Katrina happened 20 years ago. This devastating, you know, flood happened. I mean, hurricanes come inland. Flooding happens. I don't want to hear the excuses about this. You know, I saw China build a hospital in 10 days during COVID.

GoogleAudioText: And here today at the Dayton Arab American Cultural Picket, today with John Wagner. We were invited here as guests of the community and thank you very much for having us. John Wagner is a local, a Daytonian resident, I believe lives in Middletown, local regional resident. He recently did a trip to Jerusalem and the occupied West Bank. And he is here to describe like why he was there and what he did up there. So take it away, John. All right. I first went over to Israel and Palestine in 2008 and was invited over by my denomination. I'm a United Methodist and we had mission staff over there who were imploring us to come over. They were all sorts of missionaries. I mean conservative, theologically liberal, whatever, but they united in saying there's something you really have to see. And so I went over there and I saw the occupation of close, met some of the people. Of course, you met Palestinian Christians, but Muslims as well, sympathetic Israelis. And once you see it, you can't unsee it. And so that's my, that's how I got to see it. How long were you over there for? That first time was about 10 days. And I've only been there three times. I was there in 2019 and then just last month. And what are some of the biggest takeaways you'd like people to know, like that live here, and see it yourself in the end? What I think is important for people to know is that America's support for this occupation of Palestine is just unjust. And I think if people saw what I had seen, they would feel the same way. On my first trip, I was there with what's called a Christian Zionist. Actually, a couple. They were both Christian Zionists. And that means that they have a belief system where Jews are supposed to come back and take over all of historic Palestine. And this will be a entry point for the return of the Messiah and the end times. So it's not a belief that I adhere to, but she came on the trip to kind of check out her information. And I would say within one week, she had totally reversed herself. She was meeting Palestinians, meeting real people, hearing the stories of a dreadful occupation, you know, where thousands of people are imprisoned, including children. People are killed with impunity. I must say this last trip was particularly distressing. There were so many instances of people being shot or imprisoned. It's just a horrifying thing. We were mostly in the West Bank and what has happened since there's so much attention being paid to what's happening in Gaza, which in my view is a genocide. There is this is an opportunity for the Israeli government to take huge swaths of land, 3000 plus acres just since October 7th. So in the last year, and this is, people understand, this is settlers, Jewish settlers coming in and by force taking Palestinian land off the time they've gone away. They're often aided by the Israeli defense forces and the settlers are a whole mixture of people. Some are really economic refugees from countries, Arab countries, whether Jews or European countries. And they are there for just a better way of life. And they're not really cognizant of what's going on. They think they're in Israel. And these what they call settlements are actually cities. And they're throughout the West Bank. Three quarters of a million right now. And they're basically taking over all this land that's supposedly set aside for a Palestinian state. They have their own roads. The Palestinians are not allowed to drive on. They're not allowed to go into the cities. And they are also putting slantways pipes into the aquifers so that they basically take all the water. And that area and politicians, and I think it's important for people to know when politicians talk about a two state solution. I recognize that many of them are sincere, but it's pretty much a move point at this point. It's not there's not going to be a Palestinian state with any kind of concept of a state we might realize. It's all just with cheese now. But any reno contiguous state. What kind of state? You know, absolutely. What kind of differences did you notice over there being in American versus the first of the Palestinians that were living in the West Bank? Well, we have immense privilege. And it's important for us to take advantage of it as as American citizens. We are from the country that is supplying tremendous amounts of military aid. And we have some influence over there. Although our governments have not been exercising it, I think the last person to really threaten the withdrawal of American aid of all people was George H. W. Bush. And he and Ronald Reagan did too some. But it is really just irreprehensible. We did go to the American Embassy and asked him this question directly. And I'm convinced that they really want to seize fire. They really do. Americans want to seize fire, at least the administration wants to seize fire, but they're not willing to leverage this military aid, which, of course, make that more life. Did you witness? Was there different rights for you as an American over there in the West Bank versus a, isn't it, there's roads that Israelis and Americans can walk on and Palestinians are not allowed to see them? Not so much walk on, drive on. Drive on. And there are places in Hebron, for example, which is a West Bank city that has sacred troops, Muslims and Christians and Jews, actually. It is there are parts of there where it's very difficult for Palestinians to be. I wouldn't say it is as overt as that where people are singled out. It wouldn't be like Nazi Germany with yellow stars. But there is extraordinary prejudices. And they are not allowed to see the power of Palestinians are issued different license plates. Over there, even in these, these are Israeli Palestinians. There are, there's an Israeli Palestinian minority within Israel proper and they are allowed to vote, but they're not allowed to bring their families over. They have to have special license plates, special IDs. It's really an apartheid system, you know, in any reasonable use of the word. All right, cool. I'm going to wrap this up. I would say a key takeaway though that you said that you traveled over there with a Christian Zionist and you said after being there for one week, she changed her mind. She changed her mind. She actually evolved by the agreement. She actually, on the wall, God hates this wall. And what I might view is that the Christian Zionism that is supporting a lot of the American support for Israel right now, the unfalify support in the words of a friend of mine, a Palestinian scholar, just says it's a mile wide in an inch deep. I think that if Americans could see it like I have, they would change their minds. In fact, I changed my mind on my first trip. I wasn't anti-Palestinian, but I was certainly much more for this kind of idea that both sides have their claim and so forth that really isn't that. So that's my story. Cool. Well, thank you, John. John has been an active member here in the dating community. He was speaking out at the Dayton City Commissioners back in November and December, getting the city of Dayton to speak out for a ceasefire. He's been active in anti-war movements in Iraq, Afghanistan, Vietnam War. He's a man of faith and a man of action. And it's been a pleasure. I've gotten a chance to know him a lot this last year. I appreciate that, Michael. Thank you. And I certainly admire your stance. Michael has been to almost all of our demonstrations. We really appreciate that. Cool. Thank you.
